<br>
Power, beauty (because most of the characters are amazing looking), if it's something you don't have in RL can bring out the monster in most of us.  It's sad that a lot of people in game lose perspective. I agree and know that EQ won't last forever, the loot, the achievements in game can poof at any time.  It's important to just try to enjoy being there for what it is, just a virtual reality thing, however, emotions can flare in a situation where people are being jerks and irresponsible and then you have a big fight in your hands, nothing will fix this.  Hiding behind an avatar and having the power there will always end up with someone being miserable and someone abusing it.  In the end we just have to ask ourselves, does EQ life really matter?  There will be other games, there will be other forms of escaping, and EQ will become just a memory, for now I think it's best to avoid the jerks, don't help them in any way, like I said in my other post, don't rez, don't port, don't group, don't summon their corpses, don't KEI. Avoidance and making friends with people that are known to be decent is the only way to go, just move on.<br>
<br>
Haha I'm not originally an american, guess I can talk about honor then?  Seriously, if you are an adult and have half a brain and self respect, honor and decency should be no problem, the EQ environment doesn't lend itself to this, but I try to be decent and honorable, hell I play a paladin for main, and I roleplay him as I'm really a female.  I won't bug people for things, never ask for even a sow for CR on my little characters or rez, I would loot at any level and not even look back.  People in game are not there to serve me or clean up my messes.  I wish other people believed in that too.  I know a lot of people think I can be zealously righteous and a jerk, but people will only see that side of me if something distasteful is being committed.<br>
<br>
